{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte**, in *Traité de Législation* (Vol. III, Ch. 33), distinguishes the **classe industrieuse** (industrious class) from the aristocracy militaire (military aristocracy).[^1] He draws class boundaries based on **modes of subsistence and social organization**: the industrious class comprises those engaged in productive labor (agriculture, crafts, and peaceful occupations that sustain society through work on nature), while the military aristocracy lives off conquest, subjugation, and exploitation of the labor of others.[^2] This division reflects a fundamental opposition between laboring producers and parasitic rulers, shaped by historical conquests where the victors impose idleness on themselves and toil on the vanquished.[^3]\n\n**Charles Dunoyer**, in *Nouveau Traité d'Économie Sociale* (Vol. II, Ch. 13), expands the **classes industrieuses** (industrious classes) far beyond manual laborers to include **all producers of utility**.[^4] He rejects Adam Smith's narrower view (limiting productivity to material goods) and classifies as industrious/productive **all useful professions**, whether acting on matter (farmers, artisans) or on men (doctors, teachers, judges, artists, moralists, even good governments).[^5] The principle is **production of utility** (durable, accumulable benefits like health, knowledge, morality), distinguishing true industry from predation or destruction.[^6]\n\nComte's framework is historical and sociological (exploitative vs. productive lifestyles), while Dunoyer's is economic and functional (any labor yielding net utility). Neither fully covers every topic (e.g., no direct comparison of classifications), but these are the parallel discussions.[^7]",
